g.title: EleanorMonster begins.
g.text: EleanorMonster begins.

g.title: j3659731970
g.text: Drifter. What you said yesterday. About letting the monster live. Did you mean it? I must know.

g.title: j448911947
g.text: Of course, I meant it.

g.title: j3109584944
g.text: Honestly? I've thought about it some more. And, no. I'd have to stop you if you became a monster.

g.title: j3426972941
g.text: [Ignore.]

g.title: j1003964052
g.text: Not that I'm not exceedingly grateful and honestly a little shocked, but... why? WHY would you let me live? When everyone else here would be so willing to put a bullet through my head?

g.title: j3298549923
g.text: Thank you. You're an enigma to me in many ways, but now I know you'd be willing to put a bullet through my head, and that sort of thing is important in the workplace.

g.title: Chat ends.
g.text: Chat ends.

g.title: j1841695281
g.text: The line between "hero" and "monster" is blurrier than most people like to admit. I've fought against Grineer and Corpus and fought alongside them.

g.title: j3075620738
g.text: Because I think you're one of the most fiercely intelligent, wonderfully sardonic people I've ever met. I don't even think the Techrot could take that away from you.

g.title: j1199817450
g.text: Aaaand I just felt the Techrot in my cells give an anxious little quiver.

g.title: j3851066218
g.text: I don't believe in the words "Good" and "Evil." Just people. Why do you have any less of a right to exist than I do? I might not have a Techrot tongue, but I'm just as much of a freak of nature.

g.title: j12478051
g.text: How... beautifully na√Øve. And wonderfully sweet, in a tragic kind of way.

g.title: j2724958672
g.text: I think it's going to behave itself a little better from now on. Nothing like threatening the host to put the fear of Sol into the parasite, eh?

g.title: j59073765
g.text: But here you are, battling away at the Scaldra and the Techrot, trying to find a way to stop the Indifference. You clearly believe there is some line to be drawn somewhere.

g.title: j1643720615
g.text: The fact that you believe I would come out the other side some manner of hive queen with my self intact, some bizarre voice of the infestation you could befriend or perhaps even adore.

g.title: j2728200779
g.text: Boolean EleanorNoDate is now true.

g.title: j3450406103
g.text: The Indifference was unleashed by Entrati. A man. Human hubris was to blame for that.

g.title: j1357734528
g.text: Protecting people from death is not the same thing as believing something should be exterminated or has no right to exist.

g.title: j2990705121
g.text: I would chide you for the fact that the world does not function like a storybook, yet... I am reminded of precisely who you are and where you came from.

g.title: j3404842176
g.text: But the Techrot is not the Indifference. What of that? What of the more biological, terrestrial threat?

g.title: j265480033
g.text: Ensuring a flock of sheep doesn't get eaten by wolves is not the same as going out and murdering all the wolves for being evil.

g.title: j2877029037
g.text: So I suppose I shouldn't be surprised.

g.title: j2062618938
g.text: We don't really know where the Techrot came from. It could be manmade. It could be from something else entirely.

g.title: j1936769074
g.text: The simple fact is, you don't want me to kill you. So I wouldn't. I'd let you go.

g.title: j1684265743
g.text: And what if nothing of Eleanor remained? What if you saw nothing but a hissing, snarling, spitting beast?

g.title: j2623702897
g.text: Either way, I guess I am grateful you wouldn't kill me. There's that. At least.

g.title: j3636411571
g.text: And if the Techrot turned out to be another man-unleashed aberration like your Man in the Wall? What then? Would you hunt me down and kill me?

g.title: j2297255801
g.text: While I'm grateful that you would abide by a monstrous lady's wishes, I suppose was hoping for something a bit more... considered.

g.title: j69208280
g.text: How do I know nothing of Eleanor remained? You talk about how the Techrot thinks. How it talks to you. It's clearly intelligent.

g.title: j3706844627
g.text: No. I couldn't.

g.title: j353850620
g.text: Yes. If the Techrot really is unnatural? Then... it has to go.

g.title: j2304380848
g.text: +5 Chemistry

g.title: j4148297241
g.text: It seems to be a hive mind. Maybe Eleanor would still be in there, not in one place, but a billion. Who am I to say that's "wrong?"

g.title: j1380689838
g.text: You're contradicting yourself. If you're willing to stop one manmade aberration, why not two?

g.title: j1696199283
g.text: Just when I simply thought I could not adore you more I find myself once more sitting here crying happy tears

g.title: j761857324
g.text: Because I have feelings for you. [Confess feelings.]

g.title: j1090058671
g.text: Because you mean too much to me as a friend.

g.title: j998601968
g.text: +20 Chemistry

g.title: j1275025426
g.text: Asking me if I'd kill you is just *cruel,* Eleanor. When the thought of you dead, or in pain, just --

g.title: j27485184
g.text: Asking me if I'd kill you is just *cruel,* Eleanor. You're my friend. You're like family to me.

g.title: j2261646844
g.text: I have to go but thank you thank you THANK YOU

g.title: j4061236232
g.text: The fact of the matter is? No. I couldn't. Because the hope that you'd exist somewhere out there? In some form? Anywhere? Would be enough for me.

g.title: j2172770576
g.text: The fact of the matter is? No. I couldn't. Because the hope that you'd exist somewhere out there? In some form? Anywhere? Would be enough for me.

g.title: j1384187268
g.text: I'm sorry. I can't do this. I need to go.

g.title: j3247112404
g.text: I'm sorry. I can't do this. I need to go.

g.title: j346464662
g.text: Boolean EleanorConfession is now true.

g.text: +20 Chemistry

g.title: j3608726166
g.text: +20 Chemistry

g.title: j1909467138
g.text: Oh, Eleanor, you stepped in it this time...

g.title: j123372096
g.text: Oh... oh, what have I done...
